post_text:
HHS community and parents,

Thank you for sharing your sons and daughters with us once again, as we embark on the 2020-2021 school year. As we wrap up our first week, that for all intents and purposes went well, I would like to comment on a few issues:
* Please encourage your students to actively engage in all aspects of their learning (both in the morning and afternoon timeframes).
* Remember that school is in session from 8:25 am to 3:15 pm on Monday, Tuesday, and Thursday. On Wednesday and Friday, school is in session from 9:15 am to 3:15 pm.
* Students that still need a Chromebook may go to the District Office and pick one up. To check one out, students must be enrolled in the district.
* Lastly, starting Monday morning (9/14/2020), schedules will be permanently set and only adjusted under extreme circumstances.

post_text:
HHS offers 2nd round of Chromebook and school supplies
distribution

Hermiston High School will host two additional days of Chromebook checkout and supply distribution for those unable to pick up last week. Families may stop by HHS to pick up tomorrow
(September 9) and Thursday (September 10) from 9 a.m. to 12 p.m. and from 1 to 4 p.m. Students must be registered with the district to be able to pick up a device and supplies.

Drive-thru stations will be set up on the south side of the building (along Highland Avenue) for families to pick up all materials for each child in the home that is a registered student at HHS.

Did you capture a picture of your student picking up their Chromebook and school supplies?

post_text:
Parent/Student First Day Message

Dear Parents and middle/high school students,

The first day of school is Tuesday, September 8th. While we are excited to finally get school up and running, we also realize that there might be some confusion as to how to initially get started or what to do first.

It is important that every student logs in to Google Classroom ahead of September 8. Each student has been automatically added to the Google Classroom for each course, based on his/her schedule. The easiest way to do this is to log in to Google and click on the Google Classroom icon in the waffle. Please take a moment to watch the attached video with instructions to help your student access their classes on the first day of school.

Again, welcome to the 2020-2021 school year. We are grateful that you are a student in the Hermiston School District and we are looking forward to Day 1. More importantly, we’re looking forward to the day that we can hold school in person.

post_text:
This week, the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) announced that Seamless Summer meal service operations have been extended through December 31. The program allows Hermiston School District to serve meals, free of charge, to all children age 18 and younger. Children do not need to be registered with the district to receive meals, and students will not need to show a lunch card.

Families may pick up meals at all school sites, on the following schedule:

• Monday 7:30 am-8:30 am - Breakfast
• Monday 11:30 am-12:30 pm - Monday Lunch & Tuesday Breakfast
• Tuesday 11:30 am-12:30 pm - Tuesday Lunch & Wednesday Breakfast
• Wednesday 11:30 am-12:30 pm - Wednesday Lunch & Thursday Breakfast
• Thursday 11:30 am-12:30 pm - Thursday Lunch & Friday Breakfast
• Friday 11:30 am-12:30 pm - Friday Lunch

On the first day of school, Tuesday, September 8, the district will serve breakfast from 7:30 am-8:30 am. Meal delivery routes will continue but with fewer centralized stops.

Class of 2024 to 9th Grade Orientation, 11:00am - 12:30pm, September 3.

You will receive a Google Meet invitation from a Link Crew leader.

We are looking forward to connecting with you!

post_text:
Hermiston School District recently shared of a partnership with the City of Hermiston and the Champions program for the coordination of childcare when school begins. At that time the district was reviewing finances, intending to offset a portion of the cost for families.

The district has determined that it can reduce the cost by $50 per student, making the weekly rate of $140 for all-day care. Additional discounts and waivers may be available.

Families are reminded to complete the online survey, at https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/ChampionsChildcare, to provide contact information and family needs to Champions. Those interested in additional financial assistance are asked to mark ‘yes,’ that they would like more information about available programs when completing the survey.

To achieve stable cohort requirements, Champions will only offer full-day/full-week care.

post_text:
Hermiston High School announces the yearbook distribution plan. Recent high school graduates who purchased a yearbook may pick them up in a drive-thru format. Students in grades 9-11, will receive it when HHS distributes Chromebooks for the 2020-21 school year.

With the governor’s order to advance Umatilla County back to Phase 1 and lifting some restrictions, HHS can now allow last year's seniors to pick up their yearbooks. The date is set for Friday, August 28, from 1-4 p.m., in the high school front parking lot.

If students are unable to make it during the scheduled drive-thru event, they may call Shellie Rysdam, the HHS bookkeeper, at 541-667-6120, to schedule a pick-up date and time.

Attention parents!

All children planning to attend a Hermiston school, in all grade levels, need to be registered prior to September 8, the first day of school. For students to be placed in a class, receive a schedule, or check out a Chromebook, they must be registered.

Families that need help with the online registration process, misplaced the snapcode, or need to have a password reset may call the district office at 541-667-6000, Monday through Friday, from 7:30 a.m.-4:30 p.m.

You may access the student registration portal by going to the Hermiston School District’s page, https://www.hermiston.k12.or.us/apps/pages/registration/.

District partners with Champions program to offer child care

In planning for school this fall and Comprehensive Distance Learning, Hermiston School District recognizes the need for childcare across the community. HSD is working with Champions as a provider and the City of Hermiston on the use of EOTEC to meet this need for families.

The district launched a survey to determine the community's need for childcare. The survey is available at https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/ChampionsChildcare.

Champions’ weekly rate is $190.00 per student for all daycare. Opportunities for discounts and waivers are available. Interested families are asked to mark ‘yes’ that they would like more information about available programs when completing the survey. In addition, HSD intends to off-set a portion of the costs for all families.

To achieve stable cohort requirements, Champions will only offer full-day/full-week care.

post_text:
Hermiston School District announces that Maria Durón will serve as a family engagement specialist. She recently served the district as its communication officer and community relations specialist. Her focus will be to strengthen the district’s relationship with its Hispanic families.

“This pandemic has brought a new light to areas that the district needs to strengthen. Now more than ever, the district wants to better communicate and engage our Hispanic families” said Superintendent of Schools Dr. Tricia Mooney. “Maria has built strong bonds with community members over the last couple of years. We are excited to expand that connection with our Hispanic population.”

Communications responsibilities will shift to Briana Cortaberria, who served as a communications officer prior to Durón’s employment with the district. Cortaberria and Durón will partner with Graphics & Media Producer Roger Pope to form the district's communications team.

The district resumes onsite registration and Chromebook collection, August 10-13. Monday from 8 a.m.-4 p.m. and Tuesday, August 11 through Thursday, August 13, from 8 a.m. to 7 p.m., at the district office, located at 305 SW11th Street.

Online registration is required of all students planning to attend a Hermiston school. Parents of returning students should bring the specific snapcode mailed to the home to enroll the student.

Parents of new students should bring the child's birth certificate, immunization record, and proof of address to registration.

Parents may register their students from home by visiting the district's page, www.hermiston.k12.or.us, clicking the Parents & Community tab, and scrolling down to online registration.

Chromebooks and chargers issued this spring need to be collected at this time to make sure they are in working condition and are ready for student use this fall.

post_text:
Good afternoon parents!

Governor Kate Brown returned Umatilla County to baseline "Stay Home, Save Lives" restrictions effective noon, Friday, July 31. In light of this order, for Umatilla County, the district will not host onsite registrations next week, at the district office, as scheduled. The district is working with the Oregon Department of Education and will notify parents as soon as clear guidance is given and/or current guidelines are lifted.

Parents are still encouraged to complete the online registration process by going to the district’s website - www.hermiston.k12.or.us – and clicking online registration under the Parents & Community tab. Parents that need their child’s snapcode, to have their password reset or any other questions are encouraged to call 541-667-6000 for assistance.

On a personal note, Dr. Mooney empathizes with you, saying, “Our hearts hurt with yours as we navigate these challenging times. We will keep you informed as we are provided updated information to the current order. Stay home and stay healthy!”

As we prepare for school in the fall, health and safety concerns are at the forefront of everyone’s mind. Oregon Healthy Schools, a collaboration between the Oregon Department of Education and the Oregon Health Authority, is planning to create a series of short videos to address practical tips on how to stay safe and healthy. Your help is needed to prioritize topic areas.

Please complete the Oregon Healthy Schools Video Development Survey, https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSftG2gT4QEKL6jl1ZxrVtsz6Il0rYCoS_tUbKtMyFcMahQ0mA/viewform, which should take no more than three minutes of your time. The survey will provide valuable information as we move forward with this project. This is a quick turn-around and the survey will close Tuesday, July 21, at 5 p.m.

Thank you for your participation!

The Board of Education will meet virtually Monday, July 13, for its July regular business meeting.
Due to the COVID-19 state-wide restrictions and Governor Brown's “Stay Home, Save Lives” order, the Hermiston School District Board of Education will accept public comment in writing prior to the meeting. If you are a member of the community and wish to provide public comment, please email your comments to communications@hermistonsd.org by 12 pm, July 13, for your comments to be part of the public record.
To access and listen to the meeting, dial 253-215-8782. The meeting ID is 943 3818 6976 and the password is 072571.
Thank you for your understanding. Stay healthy and safe.

In observance of the 4th of July holiday, there will be no meal delivery by bus routes nor on-site meal pick up at West Park Elementary, Armand Larive Middle School, Sandstone Middle School, and Hermiston High School on Friday, July 3. Meal distribution will resume on Monday, July 6.

To see the current bus schedule, please visit www.hermiston.k12.or.us. Look under the Parents and Community tab and scroll down to Meal Delivery Routes.

Enjoy your holiday weekend!

Parents, how schools reopen in the fall will depend on the guidelines from the Oregon Department of Education. At this time, we want to gather information from parents, staff, and students to help build our plans for the 2020-21 school year.

Please complete the survey by July 2. Thank you!

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/7J3MXNM

SURVEYMONKEY.COM
2020-2021 Return to School Survey ﻿Encuesta de Regreso a la Escuela 2020-2021

post_text:
Hermiston High School, and Sandstone Middle School student councils were recognized by the Oregon Association of Student Councils (OASC) as high achieving student councils. Under normal circumstances, schools are usually recognized during the spring conference; however, due to COVID-19 social distancing guidelines, schools were honored virtually.

The high school student council accepted the Gold Council recognition for outstanding achievement and Sandstone Middle School received the Bronze Council award. Recognition is bestowed on the student councils when they achieve standards related to community service, by creating events that promote school spirit and pride, sportsmanship, unity, recognition, and leadership training.

Sandstone Middle School Language Arts Teacher and Leadership Club Advisor had this to say, “True leadership comes out during challenging times and students proved to be resilient. Prior to the pandemic, the students were actively working to keep students engaged and connected. I am so proud of them!”

HSD is proud to continue to provide free breakfast and lunch during the summer break. Please realize that there will be a bit of a change on June 15.

The onsite pick up locations will be at the high school, both middle schools and West Park. Meal delivery will continue through the bus routes and will be adjusted as needed, but meals will no longer be delivered to doors.

The summer food service program is free and open to everyone age 18 and under.

HSD se enorgullece de seguir proporcionando desayuno y almuerzo gratis durante las vacaciones de verano. Por favor, tenga en cuenta que habrá un poco de cambio el 15 de junio.

Las ubicaciones para ir a recoger los alimentos serán la preparatoria, las dos escuelas secundarias y West Park. La entrega de comidas continuará a través de las rutas de autobuses y se ajustarán según sea necesario, pero las comidas ya no se dejarán en las puertas. Las personas tendrán que ir a la parada donde pasan los autobuses.

El programa de alimentos es gratuito y disponible para todos, hasta los 18 años de edad.

Please note that the information below was originally done in Spanish.

HSD se enorgullece de seguir proporcionando desayuno y almuerzo gratis durante las vacaciones de verano. Por favor, tenga en cuenta que habrá un poco de cambio el 15 de junio.

Las ubicaciones para ir a recoger los alimentos serán la preparatoria, las dos escuelas secundarias y West Park. La entrega de comidas continuará a través de las rutas de autobuses y se ajustarán según sea necesario, pero las comidas ya no se dejarán en las puertas. Las personas tendrán que ir a la parada donde pasan los autobuses.

El programa de alimentos es gratuito y disponible para todos, hasta los 18 años de edad.

post_text:
The Hermiston School District Board of Education will meet virtually Monday, June 8. Due to the COVID-19 state-wide restrictions and Governor Brown's “Stay Home, Save Lives” order, the board will accept public comment in writing prior to the meeting.

The meeting will begin with a public hearing, providing for public comment on the 2020-2021 approved budget, which the board will act to approve.

Being a regular business meeting, general public comments will also be received.
Please email comments to communications@hermistonsd.org by 12 pm, June 8, for your comments to be part of the public record.

To access and listen to the meeting, dial 253-215-8782. The meeting ID is 997 9005 3106 and the password is 072571.

Thank you for your understanding. Stay healthy and safe.

Attention aspiring cheerleaders!

The HHS Cheer Team is holding virtual tryouts for the 2020-21 school year. Tryouts are open to any Hermiston High student in grades 9-12, from May 21-June 1. For additional information, please contact KayLeigh Wise, head coach, at hermistonbulldogcheer@gmail.com.

Attention aspiring cheerleaders!

post_text:
The budget committee will meet virtually Monday, May 18.
Due to the COVID-19 state-wide restrictions and Governor Brown's “Stay Home, Save Lives” order, the Hermiston School District Board of Education will accept public comment in writing prior to the meeting. If you are a member of the community and wish to provide public comment, please email your comments to communications@hermistonsd.org by 12 pm, May 18, for your comments to be part of the public record.
To access and listen to the meeting, dial 253-215-8782. The meeting ID is 924 5666 6253 and the password is 960512.
Thank you for your understanding. Stay healthy and safe.
text:
The budget committee will meet virtually Monday, May 18.

If you are a member of the community and wish to provide public comment, please email your comments to communications@hermistonsd.org by 12 pm, May 18, for your comments to be part of the public record.
To access and listen to the meeting, dial 253-215-8782. The meeting ID is 924 5666 6253 and the password is 960512.
Thank you for your understanding. Stay healthy and safe.

Comité de presupuesto se reunirá virtualmente el lunes, 18 de mayo.
Debido a las restricciones del estado con relación a COVID-19 y la orden de la Gobernadora Kate Brown “Quédate en Casa, Salva Vidas,” la Mesa Directiva del Distrito Escolar de Hermiston aceptará comentarios del público por escrito antes de la junta. Si usted es miembro de la comunidad y desea proveer un comentario, por favor mande su comentario a communications@hermistonsd.org antes de las 12 p.m., del 18 de mayo, para que sus comentarios sean parte del récord público.
Para tener acceso y escuchar la junta, marque 253-215-8782. El ID de la junta es 924 5666 6253 y la contraseña es 960512.
Gracias por entender. Manténganse saludable y seguro.

post_text:
This was Teacher Appreciation Week, and we cannot end the week without thanking our parents for becoming their children’s teachers in less than a month. You may be doing triple duty... keeping up or looking for a job, parenting, and now teaching!

You’ve had to learn about a Chromebook device, passwords, new technological applications, classroom management skills, etc., all while dealing with day-to-day disruptions. Thank YOU!

Know that your positive attitude is teaching your children about resiliency and growing despite the challenges faced.

The struggle has been real, and we understand! Hang in there! Your children are missed, and we look forward to the day when on-site classes resume.
text:
This was Teacher Appreciation Week, and we cannot end the week without thanking our parents for becoming their children’s teachers in less than a month. You may be doing triple duty... keeping up or looking for a job, parenting, and now teaching!

You’ve had to learn about a Chromebook device, passwords, new technological applications, classroom management skills, etc., all while dealing with day-to-day disruptions. Thank YOU!

Know that your positive attitude is teaching your children about resiliency and growing despite the challenges faced.

The struggle has been real, and we understand! Hang in there! Your children are missed, and we look forward to the day when on-site classes resume.

Esta fue la Semana Para Mostrar Aprecio por los Maestros, y no podemos terminar la semana sin agradecerles a nuestros padres por convertirse en los maestros de sus hijos en menos de un mes. ¡Están haciendo triple trabajo…mantener o buscar un trabajo, ser padres y ahora educar a su hijo!

Ha tenido que aprender de los aparatos Chromebooks, contraseñas, aplicaciones tecnológicas, habilidades de cómo manejar una clase, etc., todo mientras lidera las interrupciones del día a día. ¡Muchas gracias!

Sepa que su buena actitud le enseña a su hijo(s) lo que es la resiliencia y que debemos crecer a pesar de los desafíos que enfrentamos.

¡El desafío ha sido real y los entendemos! ¡No se rindan! Extrañamos a sus hijos y esperamos el día cuando las clases en las escuelas se reanuden.

The Board of Education will meet virtually Monday, May 11, for its May regular business meeting.

Due to the COVID-19 state-wide restrictions and Governor Brown's “Stay Home, Save Lives” order, the Hermiston School District Board of Education will accept public comment in writing prior to the meeting. If you are a member of the community and wish to provide public comment, please email your comments to communications@hermistonsd.org by 12 pm, May 11, for your comments to be part of the public record.

To access and listen to the meeting, dial 253-215-8782. The meeting ID is 988 1751 1773 and the password is 578162.

Thank you for your understanding. Stay healthy and safe.

Rebecca Pridmore, a former softball player at George Fox University, has been named Hermiston High School’s head softball coach, Director of Athletics & Activities Larry Usher announced on Monday.

“I am confident that our softball program is in great hands,” said Usher. “We have so much pride for the softball program, and Coach Pridmore will work hard to continue taking us forward.”

Pridmore teaches second grade at Sunset Elementary and has been the Bulldog JV softball coach.
text:
Rebecca Pridmore, a former softball player at George Fox University, has been named Hermiston High School’s head softball coach, Director of Athletics & Activities Larry Usher announced on Monday.

“I am confident that our softball program is in great hands,” said Usher. “We have so much pride for the softball program, and Coach Pridmore will work hard to continue taking us forward.”

Pridmore teaches second grade at Sunset Elementary and has been the Bulldog JV softball coach.

post_text:
District offers a third Chromebook for families with multiple children

Following the launch of Hermiston School District’s Distance Learning for All plan, HSD is offering families with more than two children to check out a third Chromebook. IT staff will be available Monday through Friday of next week (April 20-24), from 8 am to 4 pm, in the district office boardroom.

“We want to be sure that all Hermiston students have access to a Chromebook device,” said Dr. Tricia Mooney, superintendent of schools. “It’s important that each student continues with their learning.”

To ensure that all students are able to participate in distance learning, families without internet access have the option to pick up printed packets from the school on a weekly basis.

“We want to be sure that all Hermiston students have access to a Chromebook device,” said Dr. Tricia Mooney, superintendent of schools. “It’s important that each student continues with their learning.”

Distrito ofrece un tercer Chromebook a las familias con varios hijos

Tras el lanzamiento del plan de Aprendizaje a Distancia para Todos, HSD le está ofreciendo a familias que tienen más de dos hijos un tercer Chromebook. post_text:
COVID-19 cannot stop great competitors!

Cidney Estes should have competed at the Oregon FFA State Convention last month in the Beginning Public Speaking career development event, but due to the COVID-19 restrictions, competing in person was not a possibility.

Cidney competed virtually yesterday, and FFA announced that she earned a first-place state banner in her event.

Jenna Wallace will compete today in Extemporaneous Public Speaking, and Elizabeth Doherty will compete in Creed on Friday.

Congratulations to Cidney, and we wish the competitors the very best! We know that you will represent Hermiston well. Go Dawgs!

¡COVID-19 no puede parar a grandes competidores!

Wadekamper regresa a la cancha de voleibol de HHS, trayendo con ella la experiencia previa de técnica en las temporadas del 2011 al 204, y como asistente técnica con los Bulldogs.

“Los vínculos que tiene con nuestros atletas, padres y comunidad hacen que ella sea la mejor elección para el puesto,” dijo Usher. “Esperamos con interés ver como Becky desarrollara nuestro programa y convertirse en una fuerza competitiva en el MCC en un futuro.”

Due to the COVID-19 state-wide restrictions and Governor Brown's “Stay Home, Save Lives” order, the Hermiston School District Board of Education will accept public comment in writing prior to the meeting. If you are a member of the community and wish to provide public comment, please email your comments to communications@hermistonsd.org by 12 pm, April 13, for your comments to be part of the public record.

To observe the ten individual maximum group size, per Governor Brown, the board is unable to allow members of the public to attend in-person. The meeting will instead be live-streamed on the district's YouTube channel, HSD Communications.

Thank you for your understanding. Stay healthy and safe.

The spring driver education session is canceled. The summer session will start on June 4. You may download a form by going to https://bit.ly/39igHhS.

In the summer session, a typical schedule follows:
Class: M-F, 9-11 a.m.

Drive/observation: Roughly every third day for 3 hours.
A final schedule will be available the first week of class. Every attempt will be made to keep all times and start dates the same. However, the dates and times are tentative and subject to change.

To obtain a copy of the 2020-21 Oregon Driver’s Manual please visit https://www.oregon.gov/ODOT/Forms/DMV/37.pdf.

To ask for a refund please send an e-mail to busmgr@hermistonsd.org.

post_text:
District announces student Chromebook check-out process

In a coordinated effort among building principals and the IT department, Dr. Mooney has organized a Chromebook check out process for students without a device in the home.

On Monday, March 30, from 12 to 2 pm, the Hermiston School District main offices will be open for families to check out one Chromebook per household, enabling students to better access instruction resources on the district’s web site, www.hermiston.k12.or.us, and the iReady platform.

To keep families safe, the district asks walkers to observe the six-foot social distancing guidelines. If families drive to the district office, please wait in your car. A district staff member will come out to greet visitors and invite the next family in for the check-out process.

The district’s main goal at this time is health and safety of its students and families. HSD continues to monitor the situation and abide by state guidance.

If anyone has questions, please contact the district via homeprogram@hermistonsd.org.

post_text:
Hermiston School District has launched a new webpage with Informal and Supplemental Learning Resources. This is not an answer to “ what will learning look like for students during the closure?”. These resources are an attempt to give access to caregivers and families who are looking for educational or structured activities to do while students are not in our classrooms.

https://bit.ly/2UaOaXn

When gathering these resources, “equitable access” was considered. Are they in English and Spanish? Can they be downloaded and printed? Can they be accessed through a smartphone and not just a computer? Are resources available for students K through 12?

Supplemental learning resources are available for literacy/reading, mathematics, PE, social-emotional learning and much more.

This is not “the” answer in any way and what learning is going to look like for our students during the closure.

Superintendent of Schools Dr. Tricia Mooney is announcing administrative changes, effective July 1.

Highland Hills Elementary Principal Jake Bacon will move to the district office as the Director of Human Resources. Bacon will be replacing Assistant Superintendent-Human Resources David Marshall who has been named the new superintendent for the Brookings-Harbor School District.

Sunset Elementary Dean of Students Becky Bacon is also being promoted and will step in as the new principal for Highland Hills Elementary.

“The district has made it a priority to invest in our staff and leaders, and at this time we are fortunate to be able to promote from within,” said Dr. Tricia Mooney. “Our administrators will have the opportunity to apply the leadership skills they have gained over the years and I am confident that they will contribute to the success of the district.

post_text:
At Monday’s board of education business meeting, Superintendent of Schools Dr. Tricia Mooney, announced that S&P Global reaffirmed the Hermiston School District’s AA- (double A minus) rating.

“It’s fantastic that the district is able to retain the AA- rating,” said Dr. Tricia Mooney. “The rating is indicative of the board of education’s stewardship in their governance and oversight of the district’s finances. Under the leadership of Katie Saul, Director of Business Services, the work of our entire business department has been invaluable in maintaining this rating which equates to low-interest rates, and savings to taxpayers.”

In its rating report, S&P Global highlighted the following strengths of the District:

• Track record of operating surpluses, which have supported its maintenance of strong-to-very available fund balances in the general fund;
• Good financial management, with prudent budgeting practices, including monthly reporting on budget-to-actual performance and investments.

A series of bonds are currently scheduled to be sold this week.

High school seniors in Economic and AP Government classes got a little taste of what adult life will be like for them. They were assigned an occupation, a family size, a salary, and visited different booths to make “adult” financial decisions.
This interactive activity was made possible thanks to the Hermiston Chamber, Simmons Financial Group, community partners and Hermiston High School.

Thank you for providing our students with a memorable experience!

It is our pleasure to introduce our educators of the year. You will learn what they are doing to make our schools a special place where students want to be.

Nicole Silver, Hermiston High School Educator of the Year

Mrs. Silver’s classroom is constantly abuzz with activity where students are excelling in art and honing their creativity. She encourages her students to find ways to artistically improve their immediate surroundings with their art, so HHS is filled with color and interest. Inspired by her instruction, students constantly sing her praises and volunteer to participate in local art competitions. Recently, Ms. Silver took on the challenge of teaching AP Media Art, a new course offered at HHS. She also advises the Art Club, which brought multiple projects to the attention of HHS staff through the beautification of several areas of the building.

#ImpactHSD1920

post_text:
Last night, the Hermiston School Board approved the hiring of BBT Architects, a leading architectural firm based in Bend, Oregon.

BBT Architects was chosen from 11 proposals that were received from architectural firms from Oregon, Washington, and Idaho. BBT Architects have extensive experience working with early childhood centers, elementary, middle and high schools. Locally, they designed the Pendleton Early Learning Center, Sherwood Heights and Washington Elementary Schools, Pendleton High School, Irrigon and Boardman Elementary Schools, and the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla Indian Reservation Education Center.

“We are very fortunate that 11 firms submitted a proposal to help build our schools, and were all top-notch,” stated Karen Sherman, Board chair. “BBT Architects was selected because during the interview process they demonstrated commitment to teamwork, fostering relationships, and innovation.”

BBT Architects will team up with Wenaha Group to provide sustainable buildings that will benefit our students and community for years to come.

post_text:
Does your child need extra support with their homework in the middle or high school? We can help!

Armand Larive Middle School has a Homework Club available on Wednesdays, from 7:45-9:10 a.m. Teacher-student support is also available when scheduled with the teachers.

Sandstone Middle School has a Homework Club available Monday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday from 7:45-8:45 a.m. and Wednesday from 7:45-9:10 a.m.

Hermiston High School offers homework help Monday, Tuesday and Thursday from 3:30-4:30 p.m. in Computer Lab 150.

Saturday Support is also available for grades 8-12, at Hermiston High School on February 8 & 22, March 7 & 21, April 18 & 25, May 9, 16 & 23, from 9 a.m.-12 p.m., in the main commons and lab 150. Free breakfast is provided, parents must provide own transportation.

It is our pleasure to introduce our educators of the year. You will learn what they are doing to make our schools a special place where students want to be.

Marian Koenig, Highland Hills Elementary Educator of the Year

Ms. Koenig is a dedicated teacher who instills the love of learning in her students. She is upbeat and bubbly and her teaching style helps each of her students feel proud of their daily accomplishments. She uses songs and rhymes to engage student involvement and keep her students engaged while learning.

Ms. Koenig always strives to make her team feel included and involved in decision making. She values input from paraprofessionals as well. Marian is a wiz at creating documents, spreadsheets, and student worksheets. She takes useful data that is easy to understand, and for others to utilize with her students to help them grow to their full potential. She uses every possible second to work on academics. Every day Marian shows her love for her students and their success. Miss K is a quiet leader and a loyal friend.

#ImpactHSD1920

Ella tiene un deseo de entender y trabaja muy de cerca con su equipo.

Exclusion Day is quickly approaching -- Wednesday, February 19!

The Umatilla County Health Department will be holding "Walk-in" clinics on the following dates & locations:

HERMISTON – Thursday, February 13; Friday, February 14, and Thursday, February 20
PENDLETON – Tuesday, February 18 and Wednesday, February 19

The Wellness Clinic (located at HHS) is also open half days on Mondays from 8 a.m.-12 p.m., and Wednesdays from 12-4 p.m. Families may schedule an appointment by calling 541-667-6199.

Families may also schedule an appointment with their provider of choice to ensure their child is not excluded on February 19. Once the child has received his/her immunizations, please take the updated immunization record to the child’s school.

Snow and icy conditions can affect our schools. Should the district have a closure or delay due to inclement, the district will:

• Send an automated call through SchoolMessenger before 6 a.m. If you recently changed phone numbers, or have new emergency contacts, please call your local school to update your information.

• Send a text notification through SchoolMessenger. To receive texts type a Y to 67587. Please keep in mind that your cell phone number must be registered in PowerSchool in order for you to receive the texts and that frequency varies and messages data rates may apply per your phone carrier. To opt-out at any time, text STOP to 67587.

• Post information on district and school websites.

• Post updates on Facebook and Twitter.

• Send information to local radio, TV stations and newspapers.
• Have a message recorded on the district’s main phone line 541-667-6000.

Is one of your new year resolutions keeping your children healthy? You can help protect your child and others from illnesses and other preventable diseases such as measles, mumps, and whooping cough by making sure that your child has all of his/her immunizations.

The district is offering an immunization clinic on Monday, January 6, from 4-7 p.m. The clinic is at no cost to parents, but please take medical insurance information if you have it.

By keeping your child healthy you will not see lost time at work or medical bills.

post_text:
Mrs. Nici Silver graduated from Hermiston High School in 2002. She worked at Sandstone Middle School for five years and is currently an art teacher at HHS.

During the summer she works as a canoe river guide in Montana. She likes to mountain bike and paint.

When asked why she works for the Hermiston School District she had this to say, “I love the people at HSD! The staff in all parts of the district genuinely care about doing what is best for students and our community; our students are some of the most thoughtful and caring people I have ever met. Everyone is willing to go the extra mile to make Hermiston one of the best communities in Oregon.”

Mrs. Silver is the only artist to win both Best in Show and People’s Choice Award in the 45 years the Pendleton Center for Arts has hosted the Open Regional Art Exhibit.

Mrs. Silver married Zyan Silver, HHS science teacher, on September 1, 2019.

post_text:
Justine Cook has previously lived in Pocatello, Idaho, and San Diego, California. Her main hobbies include gardening, going on walks with her family, visiting her family in Idaho, and saving cats. She is definitely a cat lady!

An interesting fact about her is that she has a master's degree in English-Gothic studies. Mrs. Cook also likes to water ski and play the piano.

When asked what she likes about the district she had this to say, “I love the relationships I have made. Since I live so far away from family, my co-workers have become my family. My school community looks out for one another”

She is married to Clayton and has an 18-month-old daughter named Acadia.

Mrs. Mathews loves the outdoors; riding horses; camping; salmon fishing at Neah Bay, Washington; walking on the beach and, of course, making quilts.

Mrs. Mathews is retiring at the end of the school year. She will miss seeing everyone and has truly enjoyed meeting all district employees. The job has given her lasting friendships with whom she will stay in touch long after retiring. She has appreciated the love and support the students have shown over the years. Many of them acknowledge her when they see her out and about.

Mrs. Mathews is married to Richard, a retired pipefitter.

#ImpactHSD1920

The Hermiston schools have the honor of being the host of some sporting events this weekend.

OSAA football playoff games will take place in Kennison Stadium on Saturday. This is the schedule:

3A Football will start at 11:00 a.m. Burns will play against Santiam Christian.
1A Football will start at 2:15 p.m. Jordan Valley/Adrian will play against Crane.
4A Football will start at 5:30 p.m. The Dalles will play against LaGrande.
Visit osaa.org for additional information.

The 13th Annual Hermiston Autumn Kickoff Classic AAU Basketball Tournament scheduled for Saturday and Sunday will bring about 110 teams to the community. On Sunday Armand Larive’s ALTV will provide live coverage of the championship games taking place in the main gym. You can find the live feed at https://bit.ly/2D3RQ3M

We invite the Hermiston Community to join us in giving a warm welcome to the visitors that will be in the area to support their student-athletes. Best of luck to all participating this weekend!

Are you interested in being part of the bond oversight committee? This is your opportunity!

Registered voters within Hermiston School District boundaries are invited to apply for service on the Hermiston School District Bond Oversight Committee.

The committee is charged with monitoring the implementation of bond projects authorized by voters on November 5, 2019. Ten to twelve community members are needed for the committee.

Completed applications are due to Hermiston School District, Attn: Briana Cortaberria, at 305 SW 11th Street, Hermiston, Oregon 97838, by Friday, December 20, at 4:00 pm.

post_text:
Our schools will observe the following procedures in regards to recess/PE during cold weather:

• When cold weather is upon us, buildings will access AccuWeather for the area http://www.accuweather.com/en/us/hermiston-or/97838/weather-forecast/340195

• If either the “real feel” (which takes into account both wind chill and solar heat) or if the actual temperature is below 15 degrees, we will ask our staff to make accommodations to house students inside for recess and/or PE.

• Our staff will carefully monitor students while outside and take necessary steps to ensure students are appropriately clothed/prepared for the cold weather, watching out for signs of frostbite and other cold-related issues.

Parents, we also ask for your collaboration by making sure that your student is dressed appropriately (wearing enough layers, gloves, scarf, etc.) for school based on the temperature outside.

post_text:
Superintendent Mooney possible nominee to serve on a Governor-appointed board or commission

Superintendent Mooney received notification that she is a possible candidate that may serve on a statewide board or commission under Governor Kate Brown.

On November 19, at 8 a.m., Dr. Mooney will appear before the Senate Rules Committee. The committee will convene to interview and make a recommendation to the full Senate regarding potential candidates that are being considered to serve on statewide boards and commissions.

If confirmed, Dr. Mooney will have the opportunity to participate in statewide decision-making processes on the Quality Education Commission.

“I feel very honored to be a nominee,” said Dr. Mooney. “I am excited about the opportunity to learn and contribute to the tasks at hand that our state is facing. If confirmed, I feel indebted to do my best to represent eastern Oregon.”

Mr. Dagley likes to hike, do home remodeling, go to live theater and travel internationally. Combined, as a family, they have been to 32 countries and are adding to this number yearly. He taught snowboarding, followed Pearl Jam around Seattle before they were named Pearl Jam.

“The Hermiston School District has been very kind to me,” said Mr. Dagley. “I feel appreciated as I am allowed to have input in the design of the curriculum that I teach. I am supported while at the same time unconstrained to thrive. I truly love what I do.”

Mr. Dagley and his wife Rachel have three daughters—Madison (17), Grace (16), and Avienda (7).

Hermiston High School presents a show recommended for all ages, The Hamlet Thrill-ma-geddon, in the high school auditorium, on November 15, 16, 22, 23, at 7 p.m. Forty students are involved in the production.

Tickets can be purchased in advance at the high school bookkeeping office. Ticket prices are $2 for students, $5 for adults, and $4 for senior citizens 65 years and older with ID. Seating is general admission, but groups of ten or more may purchase reserved seats by e-mailing Dr. Beth Anderson at beth.anderson@hermistonsd.org.

Instead of Shakespeare’s verse, the lightning-quick, hilarious parody has musical numbers with back-up dancers and a post-apocalyptic zombie battle. Zariah Uzzell, the student choreographing and arranging the musical numbers notes “We’re having a blast parodying songs from other shows, and I think the audience will enjoy it.”

The high school’s Drama Club will sell refreshments during intermission. After each performance, the cast will be available for photos in a designated area outside the theatre.

Ronda loves to sew, read, crafts and play in the snow! She enjoys spending time at her cabin and snowmobiling with her family.

Ronda loves working at West Park. Every morning you will find her doing crosswalk duty. She enjoys wishing everyone a good morning, seeing children’s smiles and waving back at the adults that drive by. The rest of her day she spends helping students learn to read. The rewarding experience comes when she sees that children’s light switch goes off, and they “get” a concept.

A fun fact about her is that she went on a trip to Italy and Greece with her daughter.

Ronda has been married for 25 years, has two children, two dogs, and six rabbits.

Former alumnus made a surprise visit to Hermiston High School yesterday morning. Robert O’Kelley from the Class of 1953 and his brother Richard delivered a couple of special Bulldog memory albums they have been keeping for years. Ashlynn Hofbauer, Gavin Hunter, and Malayna Anderson, leadership team students, listened to his stories and presented Mr. O’Kelley with an HHS VIP glass, compliment of Dawg Prints.

Mr. O’Kelley noted that he wasn't sure if his declining health would allow for another trip to Hermiston. He was glad to donate the albums to his former high school.

September is National Suicide Prevention Awareness Month. On Wednesday, the phenomenal school counselors at Hermiston High School welcomed students arriving for school and gave out cards that let students know "they make today better." On the back, it also gave information on resources.

Resources in a crisis:
• If you or someone you know is in an emergency, call 911 immediately.
• If you are in crisis or are experiencing suicidal thoughts, call the National Suicide Hotline at 1-800-273 TALK (8255)
• If you’re uncomfortable talking on the phone, you can also text NAMI to 741-741 to be connected to a free, trained crisis counselor on the Crisis Text Line.

#SuicidePrevention #YouMakeTodayBetter #YouAreEnough #ImpactHSD1920

• If you are in crisis or are experiencing suicidal thoughts, call the National Suicide Hotline at 1-800-273 TALK (8255)
• If you’re uncomfortable talking on the phone, you can also text NAMI to 741-741 to be connected to a free, trained crisis counselor on the Crisis Text Line.

#SuicidePrevention #YouMakeTodayBetter #YouAreEnough #ImpactHSD1920

Ricardo Guerrero has many past times, but he loves to go dancing, barbequing and being around good company. He finds great satisfaction in working with people and lending a helping hand.

Guerrero takes great pride in keeping the school buildings and Kennison Stadium looking nice and clean. His biggest reward comes from hearing people make positive comments on the condition of the schools and grounds.

Guerrero has been married to Thelma, a Hermiston High School attendance secretary, for 19 years.

post_text:
Did you know?

If your family qualifies for SNAP (food stamps) or TANF, your child automatically qualifies for free lunch! Be sure to include your case number when completing the lunch form. You don’t need to worry about breakfast, it is already free for all students.

Please remember, free and reduced lunch applications are available and must be completed each school year. Click on this link to get started https://bit.ly/2kfWkP2.
